{"cursor":"3252","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n'Sigurd Lewerentz' (29 July 1885 in SandÃ¶, Sweden – 29 December 1975 in\nLund, Sweden) was an architect, initially trained as a mechanical engineer at\nthe Chalmers University of Technology in Gothenburg (1905â8). Later he took up\nan architectural apprenticeship in Germany. He first opened his own office in\nStockholm in 1911, and through his association with Gunnar Asplund became\ninvolved with the design of cemetery.\n\nTogether they made a winning entry for the Stockholm South (Woodland) Cemetery\ncompetition of 1914â15. This project was implemented initially by both\narchitects, however, the latter stages were done by Asplund alone. He and\nAsplund were appointed as the main architects for the Stockholm International\nExhibition (1930) but afterwards Lewerentz became disillusioned, Lewerentz\nturned away from architecture for many years, and from 1940 he ran a factory\nproducing windows and other architectural fittings of his own design.\n\nSigurd Lewerentz, together with his colleagues Erik Lallerstedt and David\nHelldÃ©n, created what is regarded of one of the masterpieces of functionalist\narchitecture, MalmÃ¶ Opera and Music Theatre. The foyer is considered of\nparticular beauty, with its open surfaces and beautiful marble staircases and it\nis adorned with a number of works of art by artists such as Carl Milles and\nIsaac GrÃ¼newald.\n\nIn the last decade of his life he designed two churches, St. Mark's, BjÃ¶rkhagen,\nStockholm (1956) and St. Peter's, Klippan (1963), that revived his career in\narchitecture. He continued to work at competition proposals and furniture\ndesigns until shortly before his death.\n\nKlippan is a small town in western Sweden , St Peters sits in a suburban setting\non the periphery of the town . The orientation of the Church is correct , with\nthe altar standing opposite the west doors . It is square in shape , suggesting\na more intimate ritual in the tradition of circonstantes (Standing in a circle),\nwhich harks back to early Christianity . This was the religious equivalent of\nthe search for the essential and the primitive ,strongly evident in both of\nLewerentz' late churches . These characteristics are expressed beautifully in\nthe detailing of the buildings , the choice of materials , the quality of light\nand the spatial articulation. Modern Architecture through case studies ,\nPeter Blunell Jones , Architectural Press\n","linknr":119,"url":"Sigurd_Lewerentz","recorded":1375086946,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Sigurd_Lewerentz&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Sigurd_Lewerentz&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/File:Skogskyrkogarden_ResurrectionChapel.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1a/Skogskyrkogarden_ResurrectionChapel.jpg/220px-Skogskyrkogarden_ResurrectionChapel.jpg","/wiki/File:Skogskyrkogarden_ResurrectionChapel.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.22wmf8/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","/wiki/File:Markuskyrkan_entry_side.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/51/Markuskyrkan_entry_side.jpg/220px-Markuskyrkan_entry_side.jpg","/wiki/File:Markuskyrkan_entry_side.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.